00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:43.800
So, let's look at dynamics,
reactions between chemicals.

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:47.400
So, how would we describe a
chemical reaction?

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:51.000
What are the rules?
Well, the first thing you do is you

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.600
write an equation.
And, the equation is subject to

00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:58.200
these constraints.
First of all, we invoke Dalton's

00:05:58.200 --> 00:06:22.630
Law.
We invoke Dalton's Law of molar

00:06:22.630 --> 00:06:27.900
proportions, and secondly we write
it subject to conservation of mass.

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:33.180
We write it subject to conservation
of mass. And,

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:38.450
I mean literally,
mass, not mole number.

00:06:38.450 --> 00:06:43.720
And, let's look at this.
This is probably best seen by

00:06:43.720 --> 00:07:01.040
example. So, let's look
at a simple one.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:54.530
This is the calcination of limestone.
Limestone is calcium carbonate,

00:06:54.530 --> 00:07:00.070
and at about 900íC, calcium
carbonate decomposes to give lime or

00:07:00.070 --> 00:07:05.610
calcium oxide plus carbon dioxide
**CaCO3 --&gt;CaO + CO2**.

00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:11.150
And, this is used as the first step
for making cement concrete.

00:07:11.150 --> 00:07:16.690
And so, when you think about how
much cement concrete are consumed

00:07:16.690 --> 00:07:22.230
annually on the planet,
this becomes a considerable point

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:26.920
source of greenhouse gas emissions.
And as you know,

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:30.760
carbon dioxide is implicated as a
greenhouse gas.

00:07:30.760 --> 00:07:34.610
And, there's a huge amount of CO2
that comes from this process.

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:38.460
This is also used in steelmaking
and so on. So,

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:42.300
anything on the left side of the
equation is called a reactant,

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:46.150
and anything on the right side of
the equation is called a product.

00:07:46.150 --> 00:08:05.166
So, the products react to give us
reactants.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:55.090
And, just to show some of the hidden
balance here, here we have one mole.

00:07:55.090 --> 00:08:00.180
I don't put a one in front. We
just take one for granted.

00:08:00.180 --> 00:08:05.270
So, there's 1 mole of calcium
carbonate. That gives us 1 mole of

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:10.360
calcium oxide and 1 mole of carbon
dioxide. So, here we have 2 mole,

00:08:10.360 --> 00:08:15.450
and here we have 1 mole. So, what's
the conservation of mass if we

00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:20.350
divide by the atomic masses here?
We will get 100.

00:08:20.350 --> 00:08:25.050
g of calcium carbonate and then
discover that we have 56.

00:08:25.050 --> 00:08:29.760
g of calcium oxide, and 44 g of
carbon dioxide.

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:34.460
So, clearly, mass is conserved,
not mole numbers. And, if you have

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:39.170
trouble balancing equations,
you can look in section 2.11 in the

00:08:39.170 --> 00:08:43.880
text. And, they go through some
mechanics. But now,

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:48.580
I want to look at what happens when
things are not in proper proportion.

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:53.290
So, in other words, what happens if
we put a bunch of elements,

00:08:53.290 --> 00:09:12.913
compounds into a reactor but they
are not in the balanced amounts?

00:08:38.000 --> 00:09:02.880
And so, for that,
I want to look at the production of

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:07.770
titanium by the Kroll process.
And, this involves the reaction of

00:09:07.770 --> 00:09:12.660
titanium tetrachloride with
magnesium to form magnesium chloride

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:17.550
plus titanium **TiCl4 + 2 Mg --
2 MgCl2 + Ti**. And, this was

00:09:17.550 --> 00:09:23.100
invented in 1937 by W. J. Kroll.
While he was still in Luxembourg,

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:29.300
just before World War II broke out,
he emigrated to the United States

00:09:29.300 --> 00:09:47.300
and finished his career in the
Pacific Northwest where he helped

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:21.700
make huge quantities of titanium.
And, this reaction is performed in

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:27.900
a giant batch type reactor in which
you feed titanium tetrachloride and

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:52.930
magnesium and heat to about 900íC.
And, as the reaction goes,

00:09:52.930 --> 00:09:56.790
we'll have some magnesium liquid
sitting on top of magnesium chloride

00:09:56.790 --> 00:10:00.660
liquid, and then chunks of titanium
solid forming at the bottom with

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:04.530
titanium chloride gas above.
And, this is a really clever

00:10:04.530 --> 00:10:08.390
reaction because titanium
tetrachloride is a gas.

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:12.260
So, it's obviously buoyant.
Magnesium is a liquid but it's less

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:16.130
dense than magnesium chloride.
So, as these products form, they

00:10:16.130 --> 00:10:36.260
continue to fall out of the way and
keep this interface open.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:23.660
So, the reaction can keep going.
And at the end of the reaction, you

00:10:23.660 --> 00:10:27.330
have the reactor consumed of
titanium tetrachloride magnesium.

00:10:27.330 --> 00:10:30.990
You have salt on top, and you have
titanium on the bottom.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:34.660
And, this is what the stuff looks
like. Earlier this summer I was at

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:38.330
a smelter in Japan,
the largest titanium smelter on the

00:10:38.330 --> 00:10:41.990
planet. And this is coming out of
one of these reactors.

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:45.660
This is both 3 m across,
and about 6 m tall. This is

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:49.330
