How do we know that mag will reduce

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:01.290
titanium tetrachloride?
Well, for this, we have to look

00:14:01.290 --> 00:14:05.050
inside the atom.
And as I'm going to do many times

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:08.820
in 3.091, I'm going to start a unit
like this with a history lesson.

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:12.580
So, let's go back to the thrilling
days of the end of the 19th century,

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:16.350
and just take stock. What did we
know at the end of the 19th century

00:14:16.350 --> 00:14:20.110
about the structure of the atom?
Well, first of all, we knew that

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:23.930
the atom was electrically neutral.
We knew that the negative charge is

00:14:23.930 --> 00:14:27.790
carried by some particles called
electrons. Furthermore,

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:31.660
the electron has a very tiny mass in
comparison to that of the overall

00:14:31.660 --> 00:14:35.530
atom. I mean,
the atom has a tiny mass,

00:14:35.530 --> 00:14:39.390
too, but what we are saying is
compared to the totaled atomic mass,

00:14:39.390 --> 00:14:43.260
the mass of the electron is tiny.
And, secondly,

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:47.130
the bulk of the atom is positive.
If the atom is fixed mass, the

00:14:47.130 --> 00:15:05.660
electron is tiny, not
massive, then -

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:55.250
It must be the positives have all
the mass. So,

00:14:55.250 --> 00:15:15.133
the question then is what is the
spatial distribution of charge

00:14:39.500 --> 00:15:03.750
inside the atom?
Why do we want to know the answer

00:15:03.750 --> 00:15:22.900
to that question?
Because that's going to give clues

00:14:48.000 --> 00:15:12.250
as to reactivity.
So, what do we know about spatial

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:31.533
distribution? Well,
people took a stab at modeling it,

00:14:56.500 --> 00:15:20.750
and the first model worth talking
about is that of J.

00:15:20.750 --> 00:15:39.500
J. Thompson, who published this
model in 1904.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:28.570
He was a professor of physics at
Cambridge University,

00:15:28.570 --> 00:15:32.140
and he was also the director of the
Cavendish Laboratory.

00:15:32.140 --> 00:15:35.710
Or I guess they would say
laboratory. So,

00:15:35.710 --> 00:15:39.280
he was the director of the
laboratory, and Cavendish made a

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:42.850
fortune in the 1700s,
and willed it to Cambridge.

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:46.420
And so, they established this
laboratory in his name.

00:15:46.420 --> 00:16:05.640
And, here's the essence of what J.
J. said.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:37.200
He said that the electrons were
distributed throughout a uniformly

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:44.400
charged positive sphere of atomic
dimensions. So,

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:52.000
electrons distributed throughout --

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:59.000
-- a uniformly charged
positive sphere --

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:05.500
-- uniformly charged positive sphere,

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:08.500
and let me finish it,
of atomic dimension. So,

00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:11.500
essentially you've got a positive
ball which is identical to

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:19.000
the size of the atom.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:23.300
This was termed the plum pudding
model. This is cultural bias,

00:16:23.300 --> 00:16:47.590
of course. This is a British term.
